t www.luminosoa.org to learn more. This book provides the first overview of the history and development of Islam in Afghanistan. Written by leading international experts, chapters cover every era from the conversion of Afghanistan through the medieval period to the present day. Based on primary sources in Arabic, Persian, Pashto, Uzbek, and Urdu, its depth of coverage is unrivalled in providing a developmental picture of Afghanistan's Islam, including such issues as the rise of Sufism, women's religiosity, state religious policies, and transnational Islamism. Looking beyond the unifying rhetoric of theology, the book reveals the disparate and contested forms of Afghanistan's Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIslamzAfghanistanxHistory. 0aMuslimszAfghanistanxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh  aafghanistan.  aconquests.  aconversion.  aeastern world.  afemale sainthood.  afeminism.  aglobal history.  aislam.  aislamic culture.  aislamic history.  aislamic world.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern.  amuslim feminists.  amuslim history.  areligion.  areligious extremists.  areligious ideas.  areligious studies.  asharia law.  ataliban.  atimurid empire.  awomens issues.  awomens studies.  aworld history.1 aAhsan, Sonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArbabzadah, Nushin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzad, Arezou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldauf, Ingeborg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBezhan, Faridullah, econtribu